Polymorphism — Interview Q&A (Easy → Hard)
Aligned with your Polymorphism.py topics: duck typing, method overriding, operator overloading, built-in polymorphism, ABCs, payment/drawing examples, and runtime vs static polymorphism.
________________________________________
Level 1: Easy
Q1. What is polymorphism in Python?
A: Polymorphism means “many forms”. Objects of different classes can be used through a common interface (same method names), and each object behaves differently.
def animal_sound(animal):
    animal.speak()
animal_sound(Dog())   # Woof!
animal_sound(Cat())   # Meow!
________________________________________
Q2. Why is polymorphism important?
A:
•	Flexible and extensible code
•	Less duplication (no big if-else by type)
•	One interface for many types
•	Easier to add new classes without changing callers
________________________________________
Q3. How is polymorphism achieved in Python?
A:
1.	Method overriding
2.	Duck typing
3.	Operator overloading
4.	Built-in polymorphic functions (len(), +, etc.)
5.	Abstract Base Classes (ABC) for enforced interfaces
________________________________________
Q4. What is duck typing?
A: “If it walks like a duck and quacks like a duck, treat it as a duck.”
Python cares that the method exists, not the exact class.
class Dog:
    def speak(self):
        print("Woof!")
class Cat:
    def speak(self):
        print("Meow!")
def animal_sound(animal):
    animal.speak()   # no isinstance check needed
________________________________________
Q5. What is method overriding?
A: A child class redefines a parent method with the same name:
class Shape:
    def area(self):
        print("No area formula defined.")
class Circle(Shape):
    def area(self):
        print("Area of circle:", 3.14 * self.radius * self.radius)
________________________________________
Q6. Give a simple polymorphic loop example.
A:
shapes = [Circle(2), Square(3), Shape()]
for shp in shapes:
    shp.area()   # each object uses its own area()
________________________________________
Q7. How do built-in functions show polymorphism?
A: Same function works on different types:
print(len([1, 2, 3]))         # 3
print(len("Hello"))           # 5
print(len({'a': 10, 'b': 20})) # 2
len() calls each object’s __len__.
________________________________________
Q8. What is operator overloading?
A: Redefining how operators (+, -, *, etc.) work for your class using dunder methods:
class Book:
    def __add__(self, other):
        return Book(self.pages + other.pages)
print(Book(100) + Book(200))   # Book(300 pages)
________________________________________
Q9. Is Python polymorphism static or dynamic?
A: Dynamic (runtime). Which method runs is decided when the code executes, not at compile time.
for shape in shapes:
    shape.draw()   # resolved at runtime per object
________________________________________
Q10. Does Python support traditional method overloading?
A: No (not like Java/C++). Same method name with different signatures isn’t supported natively. Use:
•	Default arguments
•	*args / **kwargs
•	Operator overloading via dunder methods
________________________________________
Q11. Difference between overriding and overloading?
A:
Overriding	Overloading
Same method in parent & child	Same name, different signatures
Runtime polymorphism	Compile-time (other languages)
Fully supported in Python	Not traditional in Python
________________________________________
Q12. Real-world polymorphism example?
A: Payment methods:
def process_payment(payment_method, amount):
    payment_method.pay(amount)
process_payment(PayPal(), 50)
process_payment(CreditCard(), 50)
Caller doesn’t care which payment class it is.
________________________________________
Q13. What is a common interface in polymorphism?
A: A shared set of method names (e.g., draw(), area(), pay(), speak()) that different classes implement differently.
________________________________________
Q14. What happens if a method is missing in duck typing?
A: AttributeError at runtime:
class Rock:
    pass
# animal_sound(Rock())  # AttributeError: no speak()
________________________________________
Q15. How does polymorphism reduce if-else?
A: Without polymorphism:
if type == "email": send_email()
elif type == "sms": send_sms()
With polymorphism:
channel.send()   # Email/SMS each implement send()
________________________________________
Level 2: Medium
Q16. Explain polymorphism with inheritance vs without inheritance.
A:
•	With inheritance: shared parent + overriding (Circle(Shape))
•	Without inheritance: duck typing (PayPal and CreditCard unrelated, both have pay())
Python supports both.
________________________________________
Q17. How do ABCs support polymorphism?
A: ABCs enforce a required interface so all subclasses implement the same methods:
from abc import ABC, abstractmethod
class Vehicle(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def start(self):
        pass
class Car(Vehicle):
    def start(self):
        print("Car engine started.")
You can safely loop over Vehicle subclasses and call start().
________________________________________
Q18. Can you instantiate an abstract class?
A: No — raises TypeError if abstract methods are unimplemented.
# Vehicle()  # TypeError
________________________________________
Q19. What special methods enable polymorphic operators?
A: Examples:
•	+ → __add__
•	* → __mul__
•	== → __eq__
•	len() → __len__
•	str() → __str__
•	print uses __str__/__repr__
________________________________________
Q20. Why return NotImplemented in __add__?
A: Tells Python the operation isn’t supported for that type, so it can try the other operand’s reflected method (__radd__) instead of failing immediately:
def __add__(self, other):
    if isinstance(other, Book):
        return Book(self.pages + other.pages)
    return NotImplemented
________________________________________
Q21. What is runtime polymorphism with a list of shapes?
A:
shapes = [Rectangle(4, 5), Circle(3), Triangle(6, 2)]
for shape in shapes:
    shape.draw()
    print(shape.area())
Each object’s own draw/area runs — classic polymorphic dispatch.
________________________________________
Q22. How is + polymorphic in Python?
A:
print(1 + 2)          # arithmetic
print("a" + "b")      # concatenation
print([1] + [2])      # list join
print(Book(1) + Book(2))  # custom via __add__
Same operator, different behavior by type.
________________________________________
Q23. What is the Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP) in polymorphism?
A: Objects of a subclass should be usable wherever the parent is expected, without breaking behavior. If notify(channel) expects send(), every subclass must honor that contract.
________________________________________
Q24. Duck typing vs nominal typing?
A:
•	Duck typing — based on behavior/methods present
•	Nominal typing — based on declared class/interface names
Python is primarily duck-typed; ABCs/isinstance add optional nominal checks.
________________________________________
Q25. How can you restrict polymorphic inputs?
A:
def start_all(vehicles):
    for v in vehicles:
        if not isinstance(v, Vehicle):
            raise TypeError("Expected Vehicle")
        v.start()
Or rely on ABC inheritance so only valid subclasses exist.
________________________________________
Q26. Polymorphism vs inheritance — are they the same?
A: No.
•	Inheritance — code reuse / is-a relationship
•	Polymorphism — one interface, many behaviors
Inheritance often enables polymorphism, but duck typing can do polymorphism without inheritance.
________________________________________
Q27. What is ad-hoc polymorphism?
A: Same function/operator works on different types via separate implementations (e.g., operator overloading, overloaded functions in other languages). In Python, dunder methods are a common form.
________________________________________
Q28. What is subtype polymorphism?
A: Using a child object where a parent is expected (inheritance-based):
def render(shape: Shape):
    shape.area()
render(Circle(2))
render(Square(3))
________________________________________
Q29. Show polymorphism reducing duplication (notify example).
A:
class Email:
    def send(self): print("Email sent")
class SMS:
    def send(self): print("SMS sent")
def notify(channel):
    channel.send()
for c in [Email(), SMS()]:
    notify(c)
________________________________________
Q30. How does method overriding enable polymorphism?
A: Parent reference/loop variable can point to child objects; the child’s overridden method is called at runtime (dynamic dispatch).
________________________________________
Q31. What is the role of super() in polymorphic overrides?
A: Extend parent behavior instead of fully replacing it:
class Car(Vehicle):
    def start(self):
        super().start()
        print("Car-specific startup")
________________________________________
Q32. Can unrelated classes be polymorphic together?
A: Yes, via duck typing — as long as they share needed methods (pay, speak, draw).
________________________________________
Q33. What should developers be careful about with polymorphism?
A:
•	Missing methods → runtime AttributeError
•	Weak contracts without ABC/docs
•	Breaking LSP (child changes expected behavior)
•	Overusing clever operator overloads (hard to read)
________________________________________
Q34. How do abstract methods differ from normal overridden methods?
A: Abstract methods must be implemented; normal parent methods are optional to override and may provide default behavior.
________________________________________
Q35. Mini-project idea: polymorphic drawing app — key design?
A: Common ABC interface (area, draw); concrete shapes implement it; main loop processes a list of shapes without type checks.
________________________________________
Level 3: Hard
Q36. Why is Python said to have no compile-time polymorphism?
A: Python is dynamically typed and resolves method/operator behavior at runtime. There is no compile-time signature selection like Java method overloading. Operator overloading still dispatches dynamically via dunder methods.
________________________________________
Q37. What is the output?
class A:
    def show(self): print("A")
class B(A):
    def show(self): print("B")
class C(A):
    def show(self): print("C")
for obj in [A(), B(), C()]:
    obj.show()
A:
A
B
C
________________________________________
Q38. What is the output?
class Book:
    def __init__(self, pages): self.pages = pages
    def __add__(self, other):
        return Book(self.pages + other.pages)
    def __str__(self):
        return f"Book({self.pages})"
print(Book(10) + Book(20))
print(Book(10) + 5)
A: First prints Book(30). Second raises TypeError (unless you handle non-Book and/or define __radd__).
________________________________________
Q39. Explain dynamic dispatch in one sentence.
A: The concrete method that runs is chosen from the object’s actual class at runtime, not from the variable’s declared type.
________________________________________
Q40. What is the output?
class Shape:
    def area(self): return 0
class Circle(Shape):
    def __init__(self, r): self.r = r
    def area(self): return 3.14 * self.r * self.r
def total(shapes):
    return sum(s.area() for s in shapes)
print(total([Circle(1), Shape(), Circle(2)]))
A: 0 + 3.14 + 12.56 = 15.7 (approx). Polymorphic area() calls.
________________________________________
Q41. How do protocols (typing) relate to duck typing?
A: typing.Protocol documents structural interfaces (methods expected) while remaining duck-typed at runtime. Useful for static checkers without forcing inheritance.
________________________________________
Q42. What is the difference between isinstance checks and pure duck typing?
A:
•	isinstance — safer, more explicit, less flexible
•	Duck typing — more flexible, fails later if interface missing
ABCs sit in between: enforce interface + allow isinstance.
________________________________________
Q43. Predict:
class PayPal:
    def pay(self, amount): print("PayPal", amount)
class CreditCard:
    def pay(self, amount): print("Card", amount)
class Cash:
    def give(self, amount): print("Cash", amount)
def process(m, amount):
    m.pay(amount)
for m in [PayPal(), CreditCard(), Cash()]:
    try:
        process(m, 10)
    except AttributeError as e:
        print("Error:", type(m).__name__)
A:
PayPal 10
Card 10
Error: Cash
________________________________________
Q44. How can polymorphism be abused?
A:
•	Assuming methods exist without documenting/enforcing them
•	Overloading operators with non-intuitive meaning
•	Deep hierarchies where behavior is surprising
•	Silent fallbacks that hide bugs
________________________________________
Q45. Implement a safe polymorphic payment processor.
A:
from abc import ABC, abstractmethod
class Payment(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def pay(self, amount): ...
def process_payment(method: Payment, amount):
    if amount <= 0:
        raise ValueError("Invalid amount")
    method.pay(amount)
________________________________________
Q46. What is parametric polymorphism? Does Python have it?
A: Same code works for many types via generics/templates. Python supports this style dynamically (e.g., generic functions) and with typing (TypeVar, generics), but not like C++ templates at compile time.
________________________________________
Q47. Why is len polymorphic across containers?
A: Because each type implements __len__. len(obj) is a common interface over different implementations — built-in polymorphism.
________________________________________
Q48. What is the output?
class A:
    def f(self): return "A"
class B(A):
    def f(self): return "B"
def call(x: A):
    return x.f()
print(call(B()))
A: "B" — annotations don’t change runtime dispatch in normal Python.
________________________________________
Q49. How does multiple inheritance affect polymorphic method calls?
A: MRO decides which override is used. Polymorphism still holds, but which implementation runs depends on C3 linearization order.
________________________________________
Q50. Design question: notification system — inheritance or duck typing?
A: Both work.
•	Duck typing: fastest to add channels with send()
•	ABC: better when you need enforced contracts and isinstance
For large systems, ABC/Protocol is usually safer.
________________________________________
Q51. What is the output?
class Point:
    def __init__(self, x, y): self.x, self.y = x, y
    def __add__(self, other):
        return Point(self.x + other.x, self.y + other.y)
    def __str__(self):
        return f"({self.x}, {self.y})"
print(Point(1, 2) + Point(3, 4))
A: (4, 6)
________________________________________
Q52. How do __str__ and __repr__ fit polymorphism?
A: print(obj) / str(obj) polymorphically call each class’s string conversion method — same operation, type-specific formatting.
________________________________________
Q53. Compare compile-time polymorphism (other languages) vs Python.
A:
Feature	Java/C++	Python
Method overloading	Yes	No (native)
Operator overloading	C++ yes / Java limited	Yes via dunders
Dispatch	Often static + virtual	Mostly runtime
Duck typing	No	Yes
________________________________________
Q54. Write a one-liner idea: total area of mixed shapes.
A:
total = sum(s.area() for s in shapes)
This works only because every shape implements polymorphic area().
________________________________________
Q55. Interview closer: explain polymorphism in 30 seconds.
A: Polymorphism lets you call the same method name on different objects and get type-specific behavior. In Python this is mainly runtime via overriding, duck typing, operator dunders, and optional ABCs — so you write generic loops/functions once and plug in new classes later.
